WEBVTT

00:00.354 --> 00:01.115
Thanks for being here.

00:01.155 --> 00:03.359
My name's Chris.

00:03.679 --> 00:11.271
I have the privilege of leading our campus in the Fox Valley area, and it really is a privilege.

00:12.092 --> 00:15.176
And it's fun to come to Green Bay, though.

00:15.196 --> 00:15.657
It really is.

00:15.737 --> 00:17.119
It's fun to come and hang out with you all.

00:17.139 --> 00:24.591
If we haven't had a chance to meet each other, hello, by the way, and good to see you.

00:24.611 --> 00:29.458
Maybe for the first time, maybe we've had a chance, been able to be here a number of different times over the last

00:29.698 --> 00:34.486
18, 19 months and meet some of you and had an opportunity to share God's word.

00:34.506 --> 00:38.612
But it is a privilege tonight as we're kind of right here in the middle of our Lenten season.

00:38.672 --> 00:44.261
And I want to welcome those of you that are tuning in online and of course our Fox Valley family.

00:44.281 --> 00:54.738
They're not tuning in with us, but they are gathering together as a church family and they bring their love as well from the Fox Valley.

00:54.914 --> 00:58.880
We're just going to open up God's word for a few moments here, and I know we have some time later on.

00:58.920 --> 01:01.063
We're going to gather in fellowship around soup.

01:01.564 --> 01:04.609
But let's just dive in.

01:04.629 --> 01:11.479
Maybe you're familiar with Greek mythology, any Greek mythology fans, probably not, right?

01:12.160 --> 01:15.745
Or maybe you saw the Brad Pitt movie, Troy.

01:18.309 --> 01:24.338
Probably if you saw that movie, you remember this guy by the name of Achilles, who was like the

01:24.994 --> 01:29.240
the most dominant warrior for the Greeks.

01:29.640 --> 01:31.824
He was just plain beast mode.

01:31.864 --> 01:34.047
He was unbeatable, really.

01:34.087 --> 01:39.454
You could hit him anywhere on his body, and he could literally take it.

01:39.494 --> 01:40.636
He could withstand it.

01:40.656 --> 01:45.242
But there was one place on Achilles' body that he had a weakness.

01:46.764 --> 01:53.714
As legend has it, when he was a small boy, his mom was dipping him into this

01:54.146 --> 01:59.112
this water that gave him kind of this supernatural ability.

02:00.334 --> 02:03.978
But when she did that, she was kind of holding him by his heel.

02:04.058 --> 02:05.060
You can kind of get a picture of it.

02:05.480 --> 02:09.085
So his heel didn't make it all the way into the water.

02:09.986 --> 02:15.533
Now, as Achilles grows older, he, like I said, he's just like this beast mode of a warrior.

02:15.573 --> 02:19.538
But there's one small piece on his body that literally is his weakness.

02:19.638 --> 02:22.962
And if you strike him there, it would ultimately be to

02:23.618 --> 02:26.882
to his demise, and that's exactly what happened, in fact.

02:27.622 --> 02:48.305
In fact, in the Trojan War, there was a warrior by the name of Paris, who sort of launches this single arrow into the air, and it strikes Achilles on his heel, and it just completely takes him down, and it destroys him.

02:48.326 --> 02:52.370
Now, I'm sure that many of you likely are aware of the fact that

02:52.930 --> 03:02.563
that this term Achilles is also used to refer to that tendon that runs along the backside of our heel, right?

03:03.605 --> 03:11.456
And an Achilles injury can be super, super painful and incredibly difficult to rehab from.

03:11.576 --> 03:15.922
Like some of you might remember, in 2013, Kobe Bryant ruptured his

03:16.034 --> 03:20.239
Achilles tendon, it took him like eight months to sort of rehab it.

03:20.339 --> 03:27.769
And then again in 2019, Kevin Durant ruptured his in game five against the Toronto Raptors.

03:27.849 --> 03:44.370
And many would say, listen, many would say of any professional athlete at that level, like if they rupture their Achilles tendon, the odds, they're not very good that they're going to come back and perform at the same level that they did prior to the injury.

03:45.602 --> 04:10.450
So whether it comes to Greek mythology or an actual Achilles injury, the term Achilles' heel is often used to sort of, it's used as a metaphor to describe maybe this vulnerability or a weakness that we might have of some kind in our character.

04:11.810 --> 04:20.705
And just like the Greek mythology or the injury, who would have thought something so small could bring somebody down?

04:22.508 --> 04:35.570
So when it comes to our character, the season of Lent that we're in right now, it sort of propels us to do an inventory of our character, doesn't it?

04:36.066 --> 04:42.635
It propels us to do some inventory of our behaviors and our actions and our attitudes.

04:44.017 --> 04:52.669
Now, I bet if we went around the room, we probably would, and if we did some inventory stuff, we probably would find a bunch of really strong character traits, right?

04:52.809 --> 04:54.271
I know we have some here tonight, right?

04:54.611 --> 04:57.815
Some real strong character traits.

04:57.836 --> 04:58.396
But here's the thing.

04:59.698 --> 05:05.586
We often fail to focus on, and what I love about the season of Lent,

05:06.146 --> 05:08.451
Like, do we ever say, like, where can I be taken down?

05:09.434 --> 05:12.020
Like, where can I be literally taken out?

05:12.080 --> 05:19.197
Like, what's the small sort of sort of understated thing that I'm not paying attention to?

05:19.277 --> 05:24.850
Like, maybe it's the thing that if I don't get a handle on it, it could literally bring my marriage down.

05:25.858 --> 05:28.322
Like it could bring my relationships down.

05:28.422 --> 05:31.587
It maybe could ruin my career or my reputation.

05:31.948 --> 05:37.417
It could actually be the thing that actually distances us from God.

05:37.477 --> 05:38.438
Like what is that thing?

05:39.039 --> 05:42.124
And the thing is it happens all the time, doesn't it?

05:43.346 --> 05:53.202
Have you ever been shocked to hear about people who maybe made a bad decision or maybe they got caught or

05:53.378 --> 06:02.271
or they kind of had this double life going on and something was exposed and it sort of eventually came to the surface and you're kind of like, what's up with that?

06:02.331 --> 06:03.133
Like what happened there?

06:04.975 --> 06:12.086
And if you really knew the full story, you'd recognize that most often it was there Achilles heel.

06:13.208 --> 06:13.688
You know what I mean?

06:13.708 --> 06:19.557
Like there was this part of their character that was sort of going unchecked for far too long.

06:19.677 --> 06:22.962
And eventually it kind of caught up with them.

06:24.610 --> 06:25.251
Now here's the deal.

06:25.311 --> 06:35.523
It's easy to sit in judgment in those moments of other people when that happens, but can we be honest?

06:35.563 --> 06:38.466
We're all vulnerable, right?

06:38.527 --> 06:47.617
And every single one of us has an Achilles heel, so to speak, that we need to keep an eye on and keep in check.

06:47.637 --> 06:49.660
And that's what I love about the Lenten season.

06:49.680 --> 06:51.602
It pushes us toward that.

06:52.002 --> 06:59.092
And at the time, maybe we think, well, it's small, it doesn't seem like it's a big deal, but it could ultimately take us down.

07:00.974 --> 07:13.391
And as you know that God's word, it not only tells us what this Achilles heel is, but it warns us over and over and over again to sort of keep an eye on it.

07:13.492 --> 07:21.042
And it manifests itself in all kinds of different ways in our lives, but I'd like to suggest tonight that the root of it

07:21.730 --> 07:22.572
is all the same.

07:22.612 --> 07:32.169
Now before I tell you what it is, let me just give you a few kind of descriptions of what this Achilles heel does in our lives.

07:32.850 --> 07:35.054
Just so you can see if you know what we're talking about tonight.

07:36.878 --> 07:43.570
It's the thing that keeps us from celebrating the success of other people.

07:44.930 --> 07:51.680
It's the thing that keeps us from admitting that we struggle and that we're never going to let people see the real us.

07:53.783 --> 08:00.973
It's the thing that sort of keeps us from asking questions because we think we already know the answer, right?

08:02.575 --> 08:07.282
It keeps us from admitting that we're wrong even when we know we're wrong.

08:08.642 --> 08:18.297
It maybe causes you to write somebody off and hold a grudge because they offended you and maybe they didn't even know that they offended you.

08:19.979 --> 08:30.275
It's the thing that causes you to maybe shade the truth about your past or to talk maybe too much about yourself or to exaggerate your accomplishments.

08:30.335 --> 08:31.597
Do you know what I'm talking about tonight?

08:32.699 --> 08:33.259
It's pride.

08:34.521 --> 08:37.586
Pride is our Achilles heel.

08:38.722 --> 08:46.434
Now, the thing about pride is that it manifests itself in all different kinds of ways in our life.

08:47.596 --> 08:50.641
But like I said, the root of it is all the same.

08:51.482 --> 08:52.584
And it can take us out.

08:53.485 --> 08:54.387
Let me just help you.

08:54.567 --> 08:55.749
Let me just describe it.

08:55.769 --> 08:59.855
Just a couple of things that the Bible says about pride.

08:59.875 --> 09:06.546
It says in Proverbs 16, 18, it says, pride goes before destruction and hotiness.

09:07.298 --> 09:08.059
before a fall.

09:08.239 --> 09:16.649
So before anything is destroyed, before something falls or crumbles most often, you'll find pride.

09:18.011 --> 09:24.299
But actually, God has something even much more stronger to say about pride in chapter eight of Proverbs, verse 13.

09:24.339 --> 09:28.644
It says, I hate pride and arrogance.

09:30.166 --> 09:32.129
You see, I want you to understand something tonight.

09:32.529 --> 09:36.594
God doesn't hate anyone, but he hates the pride

09:37.090 --> 09:37.951
that's in everyone.

09:39.233 --> 09:40.455
And it's in all of us, right?

09:40.475 --> 09:41.236
Can we be honest?

09:41.596 --> 09:44.300
It's sneaky, isn't it?

09:44.360 --> 09:45.722
It's sinister.

09:49.487 --> 09:51.470
But sometimes we don't recognize it as pride, do we?

09:52.191 --> 09:54.634
But God hates it.

09:54.654 --> 10:03.186
I don't know, maybe you're here tonight, and you hear that, and you read that verse, or maybe you heard someone say that before it, and may even surprise you a little bit.

10:04.002 --> 10:07.387
Like out of all the things that God could hate, like pride, really?

10:08.169 --> 10:08.729
Like pride?

10:09.791 --> 10:16.361
Like I could understand like God hating things like lying and murder and abuse and racism, right?

10:16.381 --> 10:17.784
Like those are all really bad things.

10:17.804 --> 10:21.730
Like we can all agree that God should hate those, but pride, really?

10:23.352 --> 10:24.334
What's so bad about pride?

10:25.115 --> 10:26.938
Like what's wrong with pride?

10:28.020 --> 10:30.103
But God says he hates pride in our lives.

10:31.305 --> 10:31.986
Why is that?

10:34.530 --> 10:51.195
Oh man, if you look at any marriage that doesn't make it, and you trace it back to the root of it, and you're gonna see probably all kinds of different issues going on, but at the root of those issues, you're probably gonna find pride, right?

10:52.076 --> 11:01.330
Like if you look at friendships that sort of break up in some destructive ways, if you trace it all the way back far enough, most of the time you're gonna find pride there.

11:02.018 --> 11:08.207
Like pride actually holds us back from having an accurate understanding of who we are.

11:08.888 --> 11:13.515
Whether you think too highly of yourself or too lowly of yourself.

11:15.017 --> 11:21.447
It can actually block us from living out God's purposes and his plans for our life.

11:21.987 --> 11:26.033
Pride will keep us from asking for help when we really need help.

11:26.094 --> 11:29.138
And some of us have been there and it hasn't ended well, has it?

11:31.490 --> 11:38.740
You might be here tonight and you got a lot of different questions going on about pride and one of those questions.

11:38.780 --> 11:40.323
I even alluded to it earlier.

11:40.483 --> 11:42.886
You might be sitting there like, what's wrong with pride?

11:44.128 --> 11:46.171
Maybe even thought pride was a good thing.

11:47.273 --> 11:51.439
Because you've maybe equated pride with self-confidence.

11:53.782 --> 11:55.244
Why shouldn't I believe in myself?

11:56.025 --> 11:59.410
If I don't believe in myself, who else will?

12:00.930 --> 12:04.495
And this is where I think a definition of pride tonight will help us.

12:06.878 --> 12:19.356
Pride is simply having an excessively high opinion or preoccupation with your own importance, achievements, status, or position.

12:21.479 --> 12:26.987
Now, this can also go the other way, this preoccupation with self.

12:27.047 --> 12:29.330
It actually can look a little bit like

12:29.730 --> 12:31.051
Like humility, you know what I mean?

12:31.412 --> 12:42.642
Like it can actually be one of those things where we're not really honest about our gifts and our talents and we sort of do this, you know, self-image management game and we're not really honest with who we are.

12:42.682 --> 12:45.365
Like those are our insecurities, aren't they?

12:46.466 --> 12:54.013
And I'd like to suggest tonight that insecurities are still rooted in a preoccupation with self.

12:56.275 --> 12:59.698
Now here's a question I have for you tonight.

13:00.546 --> 13:02.550
Do any of you know this person I'm describing tonight?

13:03.271 --> 13:04.434
Don't point to him right now, please.

13:04.915 --> 13:05.316
Don't do that.

13:07.239 --> 13:11.949
But do any of you work for this person or maybe you're related by marriage to this person?

13:11.989 --> 13:12.289
I don't know.

13:13.612 --> 13:21.047
Sure, we all know this person and this might be a tough topic for some of us, but here's the more critical question tonight.

13:21.808 --> 13:22.610
Are you this person?

13:24.834 --> 13:31.823
And unless you're really self-aware and like brutally honest, chances are not too many of us are going to raise our hand right now.

13:32.764 --> 13:35.328
But here's the thing about pride, at least what I've learned.

13:36.569 --> 13:42.397
We can easily spot it in other people, but we rarely often see it in ourselves.

13:43.899 --> 13:49.426
The reason why is that pride is blinding, I think.

13:49.858 --> 13:53.082
In fact, there's this little verse of the Old Testament, the book of Obadiah.

13:53.102 --> 13:56.728
It says, you have been deceived by your own pride.

13:58.290 --> 14:00.753
Pride can be deceptive.

14:02.115 --> 14:10.807
In other words, what keeps you and me from seeing the pride in our lives is actually the pride in our lives.

14:12.189 --> 14:18.738
And if you say, man, I don't think I have a problem with pride, it's likely that it's pride that's causing you

14:19.266 --> 14:19.907
to say that.

14:22.471 --> 14:22.772
C.S.

14:22.792 --> 14:45.170
Lewis in his book, Mirror Christianity, he says this, there is one vice of which no man in the world is free, a vice which everyone in the world loaves when they see it in someone else, and of which hardly any people ever imagine that they are guilty of themselves, that is pride.

14:47.522 --> 14:51.306
So there's two things that we sort of hold intention here.

14:52.988 --> 15:01.758
That we're created intentionally by God and he has a plan and a purpose for our life and our life has infinite value, right?

15:01.798 --> 15:04.541
Like there's nobody like you.

15:04.581 --> 15:15.954
And yet, at the exact same time, we live in a really, really big world and we are not the center of that world.

15:18.114 --> 15:20.216
There's a lot of people on planet Earth.

15:20.657 --> 15:26.944
This life that we live is not just a movie with everyone else, it's like the supporting past and characters in our lives.

15:26.964 --> 15:31.430
We're holding these two tensions in our life.

15:31.470 --> 15:38.638
We recognize how small we are and how valuable we are at the exact same time.

15:40.580 --> 15:45.426
Now I get it, Ben, you might be here tonight or you're tuning in online

15:45.730 --> 15:54.920
You might think, man, I'm really not sure that this message on pride is like at the top of my list of the problems that I face in my life right now.

15:54.940 --> 16:02.128
You might be like, man, Chris, I'm struggling with my own self-worth and my own insecurity, my self-doubt and my fears.

16:02.468 --> 16:03.689
So why are we talking about pride?

16:06.012 --> 16:15.442
I guess I'd like to suggest tonight that pride, most of the time, isn't just about you thinking more highly of yourself than you should.

16:17.250 --> 16:19.693
Pride is just thinking too much about you.

16:19.733 --> 16:24.518
And both of those paths lead to the exact same thing.

16:26.460 --> 16:37.031
Like what God desires for us to do is for us to stop thinking so much about what other people think of us or what they imagine they think of us.

16:37.131 --> 16:43.858
And he actually wants you to begin to hear what it is that he has to say to you about you.

16:45.154 --> 16:50.862
so that you can add value and make a difference to the world around you.

16:52.825 --> 16:54.367
So here's the question tonight.

16:54.387 --> 16:55.790
What do we do with this?

16:57.212 --> 17:01.578
What do we do to heal our Achilles heel?

17:02.720 --> 17:06.105
How do we rehab this back to health?

17:06.225 --> 17:12.594
If we found ourself tonight, checking our heart and recognizing, man, I got some work to do in this area.

17:14.178 --> 17:18.947
I'd like to suggest tonight that the antidote to pride is humility.

17:20.290 --> 17:24.518
But I think we need to understand what humility is.

17:25.900 --> 17:31.992
Humility isn't sort of this self-deprecation thing like, oh man, I'm such a loser, right?

17:32.914 --> 17:35.058
No, no, that's not humility.

17:35.362 --> 17:48.163
Nor is it false humility, the things that we try to manage our self-image with, like half-truths and manipulation, that false humility.

17:48.444 --> 17:52.370
And if we had time tonight to look at the life of King Saul,

17:52.834 --> 17:54.416
Man, you'd know what I'm talking about.

17:54.456 --> 17:56.599
I feel free to read it this week.

17:56.719 --> 18:00.043
First Samuel, maybe chapters eight to 15, man.

18:00.063 --> 18:07.673
You're gonna see some pride in the form of false humility on display in his life and ultimately to his demise.

18:09.134 --> 18:12.198
But what I want you to realize tonight is this.

18:14.141 --> 18:21.490
Humility is understanding very clearly who God says you are and what he's made you to be.

18:22.722 --> 18:27.729
James 4 10 says this, humble yourselves before the Lord, and he will lift you up.

18:27.909 --> 18:31.875
So we humble ourselves before God, then he'll lift us up.

18:33.558 --> 18:40.387
But sometimes when we fall into the trap of wanting to lift ourselves up, man, that's what we can be taken down.

18:41.188 --> 18:42.651
In fact, maybe you've heard the phrase before.

18:42.671 --> 18:44.613
The CS Lewis said it as well.

18:44.874 --> 18:47.618
He said, humility is not thinking less of yourself, but what?

18:47.938 --> 18:50.642
But thinking of yourself less.

18:52.418 --> 18:58.367
And Jesus, he was the perfect example and demonstration of this.

19:00.170 --> 19:03.254
Because Jesus, man, he was God in the flesh.

19:03.294 --> 19:07.741
Like if anybody had bragging rights, it would be Jesus, right?

19:08.222 --> 19:10.766
Like he did some crazy, amazing things.

19:10.806 --> 19:15.092
Like he did miracles, he literally changed people's lives.

19:17.516 --> 19:21.522
Like you don't see any insecurity in Jesus, but you also don't see

19:21.762 --> 19:24.105
and the arrogance in Jesus.

19:24.125 --> 19:27.368
He seemed to manage that tension really well.

19:28.750 --> 19:31.913
And he did it because he knew who he was.

19:33.074 --> 19:37.579
He's like, God the Father has sent me, and I know why I'm here.

19:39.561 --> 19:43.886
He actually leveraged his gifts and his strengths for the good of other people.

19:43.906 --> 19:50.994
And you can read it all throughout the gospels, like he was adding value to people's lives, both in the immediate and in the long term.

19:51.426 --> 19:58.938
So when Jesus would do these miracles, like what you would see in these moments is like a perfect example of humility.

19:59.940 --> 20:03.486
I check it out, one time Jesus, he healed a blind man.

20:03.526 --> 20:04.427
Maybe you know the story, right?

20:04.468 --> 20:09.816
By spitting in the dirt and making some mud and smearing it on the guy's eyes, right?

20:10.097 --> 20:15.746
It's a really cool example of humility because I'm thinking, man, he didn't have to do that, right?

20:15.786 --> 20:18.130
Like he could have just like bam healed the guy, right?

20:18.978 --> 20:23.625
No, Jesus, like, hocked a lugee in the dirt, and he made some mud.

20:24.226 --> 20:25.328
That's an epic move.

20:26.450 --> 20:27.071
So I look at me.

20:28.072 --> 20:31.918
But afterwards, though, he's not like self-deprecating.

20:31.998 --> 20:33.861
He's not like, well, anyone could have done that.

20:34.843 --> 20:35.824
It's just beginner's luck.

20:37.827 --> 20:39.190
No, no.

20:39.210 --> 20:40.051
Jesus, he didn't do that.

20:40.071 --> 20:44.077
He knew exactly who he was and what he had done.

20:44.318 --> 20:47.122
And that's what he's calling you and me to do.

20:48.514 --> 20:52.199
That's why we need to take advantage of this Lenten season.

20:52.219 --> 21:07.039
And we need to spend some extended time in God's Word and with God in practicing our spirituality and our Christian faith so we can hear very clearly what God says about us and who we are.

21:07.079 --> 21:14.930
Because man, if we've got our ears tuned to all the noise all around the world, now we're going to lose our identity faster than anything.

21:17.026 --> 21:30.465
So our ultimate example of humility, the way that we rehab our Achilles heel called pride back to wholeness is found in Jesus himself.

21:32.047 --> 21:43.403
So I wanna finish our time here by reading this incredible example of Jesus's humility that we are to model in our own lives.

21:43.483 --> 21:45.746
It's from the book of Philippians chapter two,

21:47.106 --> 21:49.829
And I'm gonna read one through 11 to end our time together.

21:51.632 --> 21:54.956
Listen to this beautiful example of our savior.

21:56.438 --> 22:16.082
Therefore, if you have any encouragement from being united with Christ, if any comfort from his love, if any common sharing in the spirit, if any tenderness and compassion, then make my joy complete by being like-minded, having the same love being one in spirit and of one mind.

22:16.514 --> 22:29.334
Do nothing out of selfish ambition or vain conceit, rather, in humility, value others above yourselves, not looking to your own interests, but each of you to the interests of the others.

22:30.576 --> 22:41.113
In your relationships with one another, have the same mindset as Christ Jesus, who, being in the very nature of God, did not consider equality with God something to be used to his own advantage.

22:41.493 --> 22:44.498
Rather, he made himself nothing

22:44.802 --> 22:48.467
by taking the very nature of a servant being made in human likeness.

22:49.328 --> 22:55.957
And being found in appearance as a man, he humbled himself by becoming obedient to death, even death on a cross.

22:56.718 --> 23:14.642
Therefore, God exalted him to the highest place and gave him the name that is above every name, that on the name of Jesus, every knee should bow in heaven and on earth and under the earth, and every tongue acknowledged that Jesus Christ is Lord to the glory of God, the Father.

23:16.354 --> 23:20.079
Guys, imagine if we could live that out how different our world might be right now.

23:22.221 --> 23:27.608
We're not looking just to our own interests, but also to the interest of others.

23:29.591 --> 23:38.482
Man, that's the reason we're still talking about this guy 2000 years later, like he was God in the flesh and he laid it down.

23:39.884 --> 23:45.010
He had come to serve, not to be served, and that's our antidote

23:45.410 --> 23:46.512
to our Achilles heel.

23:46.592 --> 23:57.928
It's to take the focus off of ourselves, whether we think too highly of ourselves or chances are most likely we're thinking too less of ourselves.

23:59.651 --> 24:03.516
So we take our eyes off of ourselves and onto God.

24:04.718 --> 24:07.522
We say, God, who have you created me to be?

24:09.004 --> 24:10.086
Who have you called me to be?

24:10.126 --> 24:13.170
Who have you said that I am?

24:14.882 --> 24:21.549
And it's with that understanding, we can seek to make a difference in the lives of other people around us.

24:21.589 --> 24:23.591
Come on, we're difference makers, right?

24:24.632 --> 24:33.902
And the only way that we can make a difference is when we have a right-sized understanding of our identity, our value, our worth.

24:35.824 --> 24:39.988
And the only way we find that is through our Heavenly Father, right?

24:40.769 --> 24:41.650
Can I pray for us?

24:46.626 --> 24:55.857
Heavenly Father, I know that tonight a message like this can feel a little heavy, maybe a little tough to hear.

24:59.642 --> 25:12.978
But God, in the honesty of this moment, we recognize that we all have it in one way, shape, or form.

25:16.802 --> 25:28.801
Our sinful nature many times gets the best of us, and that's God why we enter into this special season where we recognize our need for our Savior.

25:31.184 --> 25:45.266
So God, I pray for every single one of my friends in this place as they take this short message, God, I pray that we would continue to do some rehab in our life.

25:46.146 --> 26:00.447
Whatever that might look like, God, God put the right people in our path to continue this conversation going, God in our quiet time and the still moments, God, speak to us clearly, God, the areas of our life that have gone unchecked before it takes us out, O God.

26:03.492 --> 26:12.925
God, thank you, above all, for Jesus, who gave us an incredible example of humility, who walked in who he was, God.

26:14.528 --> 26:16.050
And God, thank you that we,

26:16.130 --> 26:22.219
have the opportunity to the best of our ability follow your son Jesus as a disciple.

26:24.162 --> 26:30.671
So, God, we choose to put the work in, to rehab in our lives, to find wholeness and healing.

26:31.733 --> 26:37.021
And I pray for that, God, the rest of this week, God, God bless these your people.

26:38.283 --> 26:39.244
In Jesus name, I pray.

26:40.386 --> 26:40.666
Amen.

26:41.788 --> 26:42.609
Amen.

26:42.629 --> 26:46.034
We're gonna take some time and enjoy some fellowship out in the

26:46.338 --> 26:51.026
the lobby, just one quick announcement before you are dismissed.

26:51.046 --> 27:02.886
If you do have kids here, elementary age kids or preschool or babies here, why don't you go and pick up your kids before you make your way to the soup?

27:03.507 --> 27:05.651
And you can leave the students right where they're at, they're all good.

27:06.071 --> 27:07.454
Thanks for letting me hang out with you guys tonight.

27:07.634 --> 27:08.576
God bless you guys, you're dismissed.

27:09.077 --> 27:09.938
